    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF)", content: "Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF) is the most common cyanotic congenital heart defect, comprising four anatomical features that result from a single developmental abnormality -- anterior and cephalad deviation of the conal (infundibular) septum: (1) right ventricular outflow tract obstruction (pulmonary stenosis, which determines severity), (2) ventricular septal defect (large, non-restrictive), (3) overriding aorta (positioned over the VSD receiving blood from both ventricles), and (4) right ventricular hypertrophy (compensatory response to outflow obstruction). The degree of right-to-left shunting through the VSD depends on the relative resistance between the pulmonary and systemic circulations: during 'tet spells' (hypercyanotic episodes), increased right ventricular outflow obstruction (from infundibular spasm) or decreased systemic vascular resistance increases right-to-left shunting, causing acute cyanosis, hypoxemia, and potentially death. The RN recognizes tet spells (irritability, increasing cyanosis, hyperpnea, loss of consciousness), positions the infant in knee-chest position (increases systemic vascular resistance by kinking femoral arteries, redirecting blood to the lungs), administers oxygen, administers morphine (reduces hyperpnea), administers phenylephrine (increases SVR), provides calming measures, monitors oxygen saturation continuously, ensures adequate hydration (dehydration increases viscosity worsening cyanosis), and provides pre- and post-operative care for complete intracardiac repair." },
